04617nam a22006735i 9781442687769DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182008onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426877697 a10.3138/97814426877692doi  a(DE-B1597)497004  a(OCoLC)1076416241  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aPOL0090002bisacsh04a351.711 aSavoie, Donald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCourt Government and the Collapse of Accountability in Canada and the United Kingdom /cDonald Savoie. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. How Did We Get Here? -- t3. Was There Ever a Golden Era? -- t4. Disenchantment Sets In -- t5. Society Then and Now: From an Obligation to Others to an Obligation to Self -- t6. Searching for Values -- t7. Voices Everywhere -- t8. Searching for Loyalty -- t9. The View from the Bottom: A Big Whale That Can’t Swim -- t10. The View from the Top: ‘I’m Like Hank Snow, I Have Been Everywhere, Man’ -- t11. Accountability: ‘I Take the Blame, but I Am Not to Blame’ -- t12. Power: Locating It and Holding It to Account -- t13. From Formal Processes, Rules, and a Doctrine to the Individual -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere is a consensus throughout much of the western world that the public sector is in urgent need of repair. This study seeks to understand why this is so by comparing developments in Canada and the United Kingdom. It looks to changes in values both in society and inside government, and to the relationships between politicians and civil servants at the top and between civil servants and citizens at the bottom.Donald J. Savoie argues that both Canada and the UK now operate under court government rather than cabinet government. By court government, he means that effective power now rests with their respective prime ministers and a small group of carefully selected courtiers. For things that matter to prime ministers and their courts, the decision-making process shifts from formal to informal, involving only a handful of actors. For things that matter less to them, the decision-making process is horizontal, cumbersome, and consultative, and involves a multitude of actors from different government departments and agencies as well as a variety of individuals operating outside government.Court governments undermine both the traditionally bureaucratic model and basic principles that have guided the development of our Westminster-Whitehall parliamentary system. Nonetheless, Canada and the United Kingdom still cling to accountability requirements better suited to the past and the traditional bureaucratic model. Savoie concludes with a call for new accountability requirements that correspond with court government as well as the new relationships between politicians and civil servants, and civil servants and citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAdministrative responsibilityzCanada. 0aAdministrative responsibilityzGreat Britain. 0aPublic administrationzCanada. 0aPublic administrationzGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268776940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442687769423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442687769.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK